rovide de novo glycine synthesis.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Add an independent prebiotic synthesis of serine (e.g., from glycolaldehyde + HCN + NH3 via Strecker) to break the circular dependency", "Clarify that this pathway represents recycling rather than de novo synthesis"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_008": 0.85}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.85, "pathway_coherence": 0.65, "environmental_progression": 0.78, "target_achievement": 0.82, "overall_confidence": 0.76, "feedback": "L-Threonine thermal decomposition to glycine is supported by both Vallentyne (1964) and Bada et al. (1978). The chemistry is sound. However, L-threonine (mol_011) is a complete orphan in the network with no upstream synthesis reaction, severely weakening pathway coherence. For a prebiotic network, the origin of threonine must be addressed. The ethylene oxide co-product is an interesting mechanistic detail from Bada et al.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Add a prebiotic synthesis route for threonine or note it as a starting material from exogenous delivery (e.g., meteoritic amino acids)", "Consider linking threonine synthesis to the iron-catalyzed metabolic network"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_009": 0.72}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.75, "pathway_coherence": 0.6, "environmental_progression": 0.75, "target_achievement": 0.75, "overall_confidence": 0.7, "feedback": "L-Asparagine hydrolytic decomposition to glycine is supported by Qian et al. (1993). Two issues: (1) The literature states asparagine + H2O produces TWO equivalents of glycine, but the network only shows one glycine product \u2014 this is a stoichiometric error. (2) L-asparagine (mol_012) has no upstream synthesis in the network. The pathway is chemically valid but incompletely represented.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_009"], "suggestions": ["Fix stoichiometry: rxn_009 should produce 2 glycine molecules