\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n            \"feedback\": \"Both reactions are directly supported by Muchowska et al. (2019). Isocitrate retro-aldol to glyoxylate (Fe\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed) and glyoxylate reductive amination (Fe\u2070/Fe\u00b2\u207a) are well-characterized. However, isocitrate (mol_014) has no upstream synthesis within the network, appearing as an orphan input. Hydroxylamine (mol_009) also lacks upstream synthesis. These gaps lower pathway coherence significantly.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add upstream synthesis for isocitrate (e.g., from oxaloacetate + acetyl-CoA analog or from citrate isomerization)\", \"Add upstream synthesis for hydroxylamine (e.g., NO reduction by Fe\u2070 or NH3 oxidation)\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.92\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.68,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"rxn_006 is supported by Liu et al. (2021) UV photodehydration of glyoxylic acid hydrate to glyoxylate. rxn_008 is well-established. Good Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal environmental flow. However, glyoxylic acid hydrate (mol_011) and hydroxylamine (mol_009) both lack upstream synthesis in the network, making this a somewhat disconnected pathway. The 2,2-dihydroxyacetic acid is simply the hydrated form of glyoxylate, so this is more of a dehydration than a novel synthesis.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add upstream route for glyoxylic acid hydrate (e.g., from glyoxylate hydration or CO2 photoredox)\", \"Add hydroxylamine synthesis pathway\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.82,\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.92\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.90,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n            \"feedback\": \"Good multi-step pathway with excellent environmental flow: Hydrothermal (CO2\u2192formaldehyde, formaldehyde\u2192glycolic acid) \u2192 Surface (glycolic acid\u2192glyoxylate via UV) \u2192 Hydrothermal (glyoxylate\u2192glycine). rxn_009 Cannizzaro disproportionation is supported by Aubrey et al. (2008). rxn_007 (glycolic acid UV photooxidation to glyoxylate) is chemically reasonable but the literature more commonly describes the reverse direction (glyoxylate reduction to glycolic acid). The oxidation direction under UV is plausible but less directly cited. This is the strongest demonstration of cross-environment flow in the network.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Provide more specific mechanistic justification for glycolic acid photooxidation to glyoxylate\", \"Cite specific UV wavelength and photosensitizer if applicable\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_002\": 0.83,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.92\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.86,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n            \"feedback\": \"Well-constructed 4-step pathway connecting CO2 reduction to glycine via acetate. rxn_002 (CO2\u2192acetate on greigite) is supported by Wood-Ljungdahl analog chemistry. rxn_010 (acetate UV photoredox to glycolic acid) is supported by Liu et al. (2021). Same concerns about rxn_007 as in P4. Good demonstration of convergent C2 chemistry from different carbon fixation routes (FTT vs acetyl-CoA analog). Environmental flow Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal is logical.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify stoichiometry of rxn_010 - Liu et al. uses radical mechanism with two acetate equivalents\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_002\": 0.83,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.60,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.80\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n            \"feedback\": \"rxn_012 (peracetic acid + NH3 \u2192 glycine) is supported by Aubrey et al. (2008). However, rxn_011 (acetate \u2192 peracetic acid) is the weakest link: the mechanism for this oxidation under hydrothermal conditions is not well-characterized, and the literature explicitly identifies peracetic acid formation as an open question. What oxidant drives this conversion in an anoxic hydrothermal environment? This significantly lowers confidence in the overall pathway.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify the oxidant and mechanism for acetate to peracetic acid conversion\", \"Consider H2O2 (from UV photolysis of water) as possible oxidant, but that would place the reaction in Surface environment\", \"Alternatively, use peracetic acid as a starting material if its formation mechanism cannot be justified\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.65,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.70,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n            \"feedback\": \"rxn_013 is directly supported by Bada et al. (1978) - L-serine retro-aldol to glycine + formaldehyde is well-characterized. However, L-serine's only upstream synthesis (rxn_018: glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine, Biochemical) creates a circular dependency: glycine is needed to make serine which decomposes to glycine. This is acknowledged by the strategy as showing glycine as a thermodynamic attractor, which is conceptually valid, but it means this pathway cannot serve as an independent de novo route to glycine. The Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical \u2192 Hydrothermal cycling is interesting but somewhat circular.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add an independent upstream serine synthesis (e.g., from glycolaldehyde + HCN + NH3)\", \"Reframe this pathway as a recycling/thermodynamic stability argument rather than a de novo synthesis route\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.88\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.60,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n            \"feedback\": \"rxn_014 is supported by both Vallentyne (1964) and Bada et al. (1978). The decomposition chemistry is sound. However, L-threonine (mol_017) is an orphan node with no upstream synthesis in the network. Without a source for threonine, this pathway is incomplete. It serves more as a demonstration that glycine is a thermal degradation product than as a complete synthesis route.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add upstream threonine synthesis or explicitly treat threonine as a starting material from meteoritic delivery\", \"Consider adding threonine synthesis from \u03b1-ketobutyrate + hydroxylamine analog\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_015\": 0.85\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.83,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.58,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.72,\n            \"feedback\": \"rxn_015 is supported by Qian et al. (1993). The asparagine \u2192 2 glycine decomposition is a complex multi-step process (amide hydrolysis, decarboxylation, retro-aldol), and the stoichiometry of exactly 2 glycine from asparagine is somewhat approximate - Qian et al. report glycine as a major product but the precise stoichiometry may involve other products as well. Like P8, L-asparagine (mol_018) has no upstream synthesis, making this pathway incomplete.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify that the 2-glycine stoichiometry is approximate and may involve other co-products\", \"Add upstream asparagine synthesis or meteoritic source justification\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.82,\n                \"rxn_017\": 0.80\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n            \"feedback\": \"rxn_016 (pyruvate reductive amination to alanine) is analogous to the glyoxylate\u2192glycine reaction in Muchowska et al. (2019) and is chemically sound. rxn_017 (alanine-glyoxylate transamination) is a well-known biological reaction and plausible under prebiotic iron catalysis. However, both pyruvate (mol_022) and hydroxylamine (mol_009) lack upstream synthesis in the network. The net reaction is essentially transferring an amino group from hydroxylamine to glyoxylate via a pyruvate/alanine shuttle, which is more complex than the direct reductive amination (P2) with no clear advantage. The regeneration of pyruvate as a catalyst is elegant but adds complexity without clear benefit.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add upstream pyruvate synthesis (e.g., from CO2 reduction or acetaldehyde carboxylation)\", \"Consider whether this pathway adds value beyond P2's direct reductive amination\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-constructed and comprehensive synthesis network for glycine with excellent literature alignment. The network successfully implements all six major experimentally demonstrated pathways from the literature review (cyanosulfidic, iron-catalyzed reductive amination, peracetic acid amination, serine decomposition, threonine decomposition, asparagine decomposition) and adds creative extensions (acetate photoredox routes, transamination pathway). Key strengths: (1) Outstanding literature alignment - nearly every reaction maps to a cited experimental study; (2) Good hub molecule identification - glyoxylate, formaldehyde, glycolic acid, and ammonia are correctly identified as central nodes; (3) Multiple convergent pathways to glycine through t