thways to glycine across three environments: Hydrothermal (iron-catalyzed reductive amination, thermal decomposition of higher amino acids, peracetic acid amination), Surface (Strecker/cyanosulfidic aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis, UV photoredox routes via glyoxylate), and Biochemical (downstream peptide assembly). The network is anchored by five hub molecules \u2014 glyoxylate, formaldehyde, ammonia, acetate, and glycine itself \u2014 each participating in \u22653 reactions. Glyoxylate serves as the principal convergence point: four independent upstream reactions feed it (isocitrate cleavage, UV dehydration of dihydroxyacetic acid, glycolic acid photooxidation, and glycolic acid itself from Cannizzaro/photoredox), and it is reductively aminated to glycine by iron catalysis. Glycolic acid is NOT a dead-end: it is explicitly connected to glyoxylate via UV photooxidation (Liu et al., 2021). All orphan molecules from previous attempts are addressed: hydroxylamine is synthesized from NO reduction by Fe\u2070, serine has a non-circular upstream (Strecker from glycolaldehyde), and threonine/asparagine are marked as exogenous starting materials from meteoritic delivery (Pizzarello et al., 2006). Stoichiometric errors are corrected: asparagine yields 2 glycine, Cannizzaro requires 2 formaldehyde. Every hydrothermal and surface reaction specifies mineral agents.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"